06663nam a22013095i 9780691223292DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20221998nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020759384  a97806912232927 a10.1515/97806912232922doi  a(DE-B1597)573862  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aDS740.5.S65 4aDS740.5.S65bS562 1997eb 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a327.510472221 aSheng, Michael M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBattling Western Imperialism :bMao, Stalin, and the United States /cMichael M. Sheng. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource (267 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter I. The Roots of Mao's Pro-Soviet Policy before 1937 -- tChapter II. CCP-Moscow Relations during the Anti-Japanese War, 1937-1945 -- tChapter III. From Enemies to Friends: CCP Policy toward the United States before Pearl Harbor -- tChapter IV. Courting the Americans: The CCP's United Front Policy toward the U.S., 1942-1945 -- tChapter V. Postwar Alignment: CCP-Moscow versus GMD-Washington in Manchuria, August-December 1945 -- tChapter VI. Mao Deals with George Marshall, November 1945-December 1946 -- tChapter VII. The CCP and the Cold War in Asia: Mao's "Intermediate-Zone" Theory and the Anti-American United Front, 1946-1947 -- tChapter VIII. Mao's Revolutionary Diplomacy and the Cold War in Asia, 1948-1949 -- tConclusion -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the central issues in the study of the Chinese Communist Party and its foreign policy is its relations with Moscow. Was the CCP a Chinese nationalist party antagonistic to an intrusive Soviet Union or was it rather an internationalist party with ideological-political and strategic-military ties to Moscow, faithfully adhering to Marxist-Leninist principles as well as to Stalin's policy advice? For the past two decades a number of historians have argued that the CCP was a nationalist movement and that the United States missed its opportunity to establish friendly relations because U.S. leaders were blinded by fears of an international Communist threat. In his provocative book, Michael Sheng strongly challenges this position. On the basis of extensive new information obtained from recently available Chinese sources, Sheng demonstrates that the foreign policy of the CCP under Mao Zedong did, in fact, follow the directions recommended by Joseph Stalin. Sheng reveals that Mao and Stalin were in frequent and direct contact by radio and by correspondence, beginning in 1936, and that Mao consistently acted on Stalin's advice. Battling Western Imperialism analyzes the CCP's relations with both the Soviet Union and the United States and provides conclusive evidence that there was no "lost opportunity" for the U.S. in China. He shows that the CCP viewed the United States as a hostile capitalist power that opposed its revolutionary aims. The author has drawn on an unprecedented collection of Chinese-language materials to make a powerful new argument.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh  aAcheson, Dean.  aAmerasia Case.  aAtlantic Charter.  aBao Erhan.  aBeitaihe railway station.  aBell Act.  aBraun, Otto.  aCabot, John M.  aCessation of Hostilities Order.  aChen Jian.  aChen Yun.  aConfucianism.  aCurrie, Lauchlin.  aDeng Liqun.  aDeng Xiaoping.  aDiplomatic Clique.  aDong Biwu.  aEighth Congress (CCP).  aExport-Import Bank.  aFengtian Clique.  aFifth Plenum.  aForeign Affairs Group.  aGMD-Japan joint force.  aGao Shuxun.  aGrea